Introduction & Problem Description

The aim of this study to predict tomorrow’s hourly electricity consumption of Turkey. The data is downloaded from EPIAS. The time range is 01.01.2016-20.05.2021.

Preparing and Adjustments

Reading Data

I download the data via read.csv function.

raw_data <- read.csv("C:\\Users\\aadem\\OneDrive\\Desktop\\ConsumptionData.csv")
head(raw_data)
##         Date  Hour Consumption..MWh.
## 1 01.01.2016 00:00         26,277.24
## 2 01.01.2016 01:00         24,991.82
## 3 01.01.2016 02:00         23,532.61
## 4 01.01.2016 03:00         22,464.78
## 5 01.01.2016 04:00         22,002.91
## 6 01.01.2016 05:00         21,957.08
hourly_data <- raw_data %>%
  mutate(date_hour=paste(Date,Hour,sep = " ")) %>%
  mutate(date=as.POSIXct(date_hour,format="%d.%m.%Y %H:%M"),consumption=as.numeric(gsub(",","",Consumption..MWh.))) %>%
  select(date,consumption)

Visual Analysis

To reach a better understand about the data, we should plot it.

ggplot(hourly_data,aes(x=date,y=consumption))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title="Hourly Electricity Consumption(MW/h)")

The first thing that caught my eye is that there is a 0 consumption value in 2016, This null value may prevent making healthy analyzes. So, I should assign a new logical value to this row. Taking average of previous and next hour seems to be logical.

i <- which.min(hourly_data$consumption)
hourly_data[i,'consumption'] <- mean(c(hourly_data[i-1,'consumption'],hourly_data[i+1,'consumption']))
ggplot(hourly_data,aes(x=date,y=consumption))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(title="Hourly Electricity Consumption(MW/h)")

When we check the data visually, we see an increased use of electricity during the summer months. In addition, due to reasons that are caused by pandemic, electricity consumption deviated from normal levels in the spring of 2020. And finally, there were sudden deviations in some periods. Religious and public holidays may have caused this situation. According to the data published by EPİAŞ on a profile basis, the high share of commercial and industrial enterprises in electricity consumption makes this situation logical.

As a result, it’s hard to say data is stationary according to visual testing.However, it is necessary to prove this comment with more quantitative methods.So, we can plot autocorrelation function.

acf(hourly_data$consumption)

We see a very high autocorrelation. Thus, the results of the autocorrelation function and the results of the visual analysis were compatible.

Time Frame Adjustments

The time frame in the original data source is specified as hourly.However, I will use data from multiple time frames in analysis. So, I created data in multiple time frame before starting analysis.

daily_data <- hourly_data %>%
  group_by(date(date)) %>%
  summarise(consumption=mean(consumption)) %>%
  rename(date='date(date)')
weekly_data <- daily_data %>%
  group_by(yearweek(date)) %>%
  summarise(consumption=mean(consumption)) %>%
  rename(yearweek='yearweek(date)')
monthly_data <- daily_data %>%
  group_by(yearmonth(date)) %>%
  summarise(consumption=mean(consumption)) %>%
  rename(month='yearmonth(date)')

Task 1- Decomposition

Hourly Level

ts_hourly_data <- ts(hourly_data$consumption, frequency = 24)

When we visually check the data in hourly basis, we decided that additive model would be a greater choice for this time series rather than multiplicative. We should decompose the data into trend, seasonal, remainder component via decompose function.

Let’s use decompose() function to decompose the series into trend, seasonal, and random component.

decomposed_hourly_data <- decompose(ts_hourly_data, type="additive")
plot(hourly_data)

plot(decomposed_hourly_data)

After looking decomposition chart of daily series, we can say that there is random component that follow zero mean and equal variance. Also, both an increasing and a decreasing trend can be mentioned. However,hourly analysis may not yield logical results.

Daily Level

plot(daily_data)

Visually, one can talk about seasonality in daily data.

acf(daily_data$consumption)

There is a seasonality in lag=7.

ts_daily_data <- ts(daily_data$consumption, frequency = 7)
decomposed_daily_data <- decompose(ts_daily_data, type = "additive")
plot(decomposed_daily_data)

The hourly data gave more insight than the daily data. Some exceptional values, especially in the random part, have become more clear. However, generally, Constant mean assumption is satisfied and variance does not change much.

Weekly Level

plot(weekly_data)

acf(weekly_data$consumption)

ts_weekly_data <- ts(weekly_data$consumption, frequency = 7)
decomposed_weekly_data <- decompose(ts_weekly_data, type = "additive")
plot(decomposed_weekly_data)

Monthly Level

plot(monthly_data)

acf(monthly_data$consumption)

ts_monthly_data <- ts(monthly_data$consumption, frequency = 7)
decomposed_monthly_data <- decompose(ts_monthly_data, type = "additive")
plot(decomposed_monthly_data)

# Task 2

For rest of this report, we will continue with the decomposed data with frequency=(7*24).That is we think that both the hour and the day of the observation define the seasonality of our data.

ts_hd <- ts(hourly_data$consumption, frequency = 24*7)
decomposed_hd <- decompose(ts_hd, type = "additive")
plot(decomposed_hd)

random_hd <- decomposed_hd$random
plot(random_hd)

trend_hd <- decomposed_hd$trend
plot(trend_hd)

seasonal_hd <- decomposed_hd$seasonal
plot(seasonal_hd)

Random part satisfies the assumptions that it follows 0 mean and constant variance. Also, We can see a seasonality in trend.
